text:
Lose weight right! Diet for breastfeeding a newborn
How to stay fit in a difficult period for the body? We tell you what the correct diet is when breastfeeding a newborn.
07 Nov 2019, 11:00 by Tatyana Shamanina
Is your goal to lose weight while breastfeeding? First of all, consult a doctor - any wrong step can affect the health of the child. We tell you what the right diet for breastfeeding consists of.
Mom's diet for weight loss while breastfeeding a newborn: general principles
Follow basic guidelines to gradually lose weight during lactation.

Eat high protein foods 2–3 times a day.
Eat three small servings of vegetables every day.
Add two small servings of fruit to the menu every day.
Include whole grains in your daily diet.
Drink water only to quench your thirst. No need to force yourself to drink a certain amount of liquid.
If you adhere to a vegetarian lifestyle, then you need to take supplements B12.

How much is a breastfeeding diet?
Breastfeeding requires extra calories. Adjust calories - determine your individual amount per day and add another 500 calories to it. Only after the child begins to eat other foods can you reduce calories. Remember, you do not “save” extra calories in yourself, but give it to the child.
Can I drink coffee while breastfeeding?
Of course, caffeine gets into milk, but for most children this does not interfere. However, remember that if your child does not sleep well or is irritated, you should reduce the amount of caffeine or completely abandon it. Some studies show that newborns are more sensitive to caffeine than older children. So a preliminary consultation with a doctor will not hurt.
Mom's monthly breastfeeding diet
1st and 2nd months
To help the baby adapt to the new conditions, in the first month the diet during feeding should be strict. No exotic, greasy and harmful foods and dishes.
What the diet consists of in the 1st month:

cereals, including millet, buckwheat and oatmeal;
low-fat steamed or boiled meat;
dairy products, including cottage cheese - no more than three times a week;
fish - twice a week;
dried fruits compote;
wholemeal bread and pasta;
oil - no more than 2 tablespoons per day.
boiled and fresh vegetables - about 500 g per day, avoid cabbage, garlic and onions.

2 to 6 months
The following products and dishes can be added to the menu:




meatless borscht seasoned with tomato juice;
nuts, except peanuts and pistachios;
poultry meat;
homemade jam or jam and honey;
fresh onions;
fresh and dried herbs, such as lemon balm, mint, basil and thyme. Gradually add exotic fruits, seafood, garlic and beans to your diet and watch the baby react.

6 months to a year
The diet when feeding a newborn from six months to a year includes a more diverse diet. Eat only boiled, stewed or steamed food. Gradually add exotic fruits, seafood, garlic and beans to your diet and watch the baby react. Do not eat harmful fatty foods, such as condensed milk, sausages, ice cream, pickles and smoked meats.
Breastfeeding Diet: Product List
When forming a nutrition plan, you should understand that a child may develop a food allergy to the foods you consume. In this case, you need to contact a specialist to identify which particular product has caused allergies, in order to exclude it.
Allowed Products:

dietary meat, poultry;
fish, including salmon, sardine and cod;
eggs
medium-fat dairy products;
beans, nuts, dried fruits and seeds;
vegetables, including dark green and yellow fruits;
fruits without allergens;
whole grains and cereals, including bread, pasta, cereal and oatmeal.

Prohibited Products
Avoid finished processed foods from stores that are high in calories, sugar, and unhealthy fats, as well as:

chocolate;
spices, including cinnamon, garlic, curry, chili pepper;
citrus fruits and their juices, such as orange, lemon, lime and grapefruit;
Strawberry;
kiwi;
a pineapple;
fruit with a laxative effect, such as cherries and prunes.

